    - severability - severability:
  enforceability: CONDITIONAL
  baseline: intent_based_common_law
  summary: >
    Colorado courts enforce severability clauses when the contract shows
    that the parties intended invalid provisions to be severable from
    the remainder of the agreement. Even without an express severability
    clause, courts may sever an unenforceable term if doing so does not
    defeat the contractâ€™s primary purpose.
  consumer_impact: >
    Severability protects consumers from losing an entire agreement due
    to one unlawful or invalid clause, while still allowing courts to
    strike unfair or illegal provisions.
  authority:
    case_law:
      - name: City of Golden v. Parker
       citation: 928 P.2d 114 (Colo. 1996)
       principle: >  Severability depends on contract language, structure, and
       whether the remaining provisions can operate independently.
  sources:
    - https://law.justia.com/cases/colorado/supreme-court/1996/95sc193-0.html
  confidence: HIGH


